Russia debates its future
JAROSLAWL: Russia, many say, lacks a "civil society."
But it partially compensates for this with a rather interesting public space, where serious topics are debated and where fleeting glances at the powerful are not entirely limited to TV clips.
In the first two weeks of September, there were consecutive meetings of two important Russian political groups, the Valdai Discussion Club and the Global Policy Forum.
The first took place on a ship and ended with a dinner with Prime Minister Vladimir Putin in Sochi on the Black Sea.
The latter, in Jaroslawl, culminated in a symposium with President Dmitri Medvedev.
Scientists, members of think tanks and journalists (both Russian and foreign) discussed together with important politicians and business leaders about Russia's future.
Three things made these events, in a typically Russian way, something special.
The first was the intense media interest.
Even a very camera-shy scientist could suddenly find himself becoming a Russian TV star.
The second was the willingness of both Putin and Medvedev to engage publicly with experts on their own intellectual terrain.
I can think of only one recent Western political leader who had the confidence to do this; it was Bill Clinton.
And finally, the two events marked the emergence of two rival political forums, each exuding a weak but unmistakable aroma of an impending conflict.
For someone with eyes in their head, these two conferences offered a fascinating insight into a crumbling diarchy.
The main topic of the Valdai Conference was whether Russia's history and geography condemned it to authoritarian rule.
Falls the democracy belongs to the future, then is it Russia's fate to miss it?
The pessimists – especially Russian historians – argued that it would be difficult, if not impossible, for Russia to overcome its autocratic heritage.
Lew Beloussow from the Lomonosov State University in Moscow argued that autocracy in Russia rises again and again like a phoenix from the ashes, supported by the passivity and endurance of the Russians.
The Bolsheviks had inherited autocracy from the Tsars; Putin had rediscovered the old monarchical principle of anointed succession and thus bypassed the democratic competition for the presidency.
Radicals like Vladimir Ryschkow rejected this historical determinism. One should not legitimize authoritarianism by reference to history, Ryschkow argued.
The protests were increasing.
It was the yoke of Putin, not that of history, which was heavy upon Russia.
Many in this discussion lacked clarity, as is typically the case in such discussions.
Most participants failed to distinguish between history as a limitation and history as a determinant.
Countries and civilizations can never fully overcome their history, but every history offers many different possibilities.
Countries are not genetically programmed like animals.
The discussion about autocracy was inevitably linked to that of other topics.
Autocracy in Russia has been defended as necessary for a world empire.
Yet this raises another question: Does Russia need a world empire?
Can Russia renounce its imperial past and maintain normal relations with its recently independent neighbors, such as Ukraine and Georgia?
Can it really be a completely "normal" actor on the world stage?
At the conference in Jaroslawl with Medvedev, the focus shifted to the connection between democracy and modernization.
All agreed that Russia must diversify its economy and overcome its dependence on energy.
As Medvedev emphasized, an economy based on raw materials is always vulnerable to fluctuations in commodity prices.
Yet there are broadly speaking two views on the relationship between political and economic modernization.
Putin's view is that democracy results from a modern national economy, as a kind of reward for the hard work done.
If the state from above promotes modernization, then democracy will naturally grow, albeit slowly, due to increasing prosperity and a growing middle class.
The chief ideologue of the Kremlin, Vladimir Surkov, has suggested that a real democracy requires a "democracy in the mind," and thus implies that this desirable mental state is still far away in Russia.
The alternative view, held by people like Igor Jurgens, head of Medvedev's preferred think tank, the Institute of Contemporary Development, is that democracy is a prerequisite for economic modernization.
They argue that the current form of the Russian state lacks any real incentive to reform its own bad economic habits – or those of the Russians.
The previous development confirms this.
Russia has experienced a modest recovery from the recession.
Yet there is almost no innovation; the elites are content to lead a comfortable life through earnings from the energy business, and corruption continues unchecked.
Putin is the strong leader of a weak state, which, since it lacks a mobilizing element or feedback process, is unable to carry out a modernization project.
There is a clear divide between Putin and Medvedev.
Medvedev is anything but Putin's puppet.
Both believe that democracy must come sooner or later, but with Putin the emphasis is clearly on the "later," while Medvedev has added a liberating voice to the public discourse in Russia.
Skeptics claim this is merely a misleading routine following the motto "Good Cop, Bad Cop."
But words count, and a new rhetoric is a political force in its own right.
Medvedev's main strategic goal must now be to secure a second term as president.
He cannot openly question Putin's legacy, but must position himself as someone who goes beyond Putin.
It is a difficult balancing act, because Putin can always reclaim the presidency whenever he believes his former protégé wants to dismantle the authoritarian state that Putin created.
Nineteen years after the fall of communism, Russia's direction remains as unclear as ever.
This is especially important for the Russians, yet because Russia spans the vast Eurasian landmass, the lack of clarity regarding Russia's future forces the rest of us to constantly worry.
Is Russia part of the West?
Does lending him his history and geography a uniquely Eurasian perspective, which is capable of resolving a potential clash between the Western and Eastern civilizations or between Christianity and Islam?
Russia cannot be neatly categorized into geopolitical categories, but it remains too important to ignore.
